<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: DOWNEY; APPEALS COURT 
TO TAKE UP ISSUE OF ANONYMOUS JURIES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A state appeals court has ordered that a Downey trial be postponed until the 
justices can decide whether an anonymous jury should be used. 
</P>
<P>
 In a brief order, the 2nd District Court of Appeal said that the use of 
anonymous juries raises a "novel and important issue of law."The court asked 
that additional written briefs be submitted and scheduled oral arguments for 
Dec. 21. 
</P>
<P>
 The Downey case, in which Dennis Jansen is accused of violating a restraining 
order, has been closely watched because it could be the first to resolve 
whether jurors can be anonymous without a compelling reason such as the threat 
of injury or harassment. 
</P>
<P>
 The judge in that case, John David Lord, and a Bellflower judge, Philip K. 
Mautino, have drawn attention and legal challenges because they use anonymous 
juries in every criminal case. 
</P>
</TEXT>
