<HEADLINE>
<P>
TV RATINGS; ABC WINS FIRST TWO WEEKS OF THE SEASON 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By LEE MARGULIES 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 NBC had the two highest-rated rookie programs last week, but ABC had the most 
to crow about when the weekly prime-time figures from the A.C. Nielsen Co. came 
out Tuesday: For the first time since 1978, it has won the first two weeks of 
the season.  
</P>
<P>
 Three-time defending champion CBS, meanwhile, is running third--the only one 
of the four networks to have registered a decline in audience. 
</P>
<P>
 ABC had the top-rated show of the week in "Home Improvement" and placed three 
others in the Top 10: "Grace Under Fire," "Roseanne" and "Monday Night 
Football" (Denver Broncos at Buffalo Bills). Its new sitcom "Me and the Boys" 
tied for 14th among the week's 95 prime-time network programs. 
</P>
<P>
 NBC, whose ratings are up 13% so far this season, had three new series in the 
Top 20: the medical drama "ER" with Anthony Edwards at No. 6, "Madman of the 
People" at No. 10 and "Friends" at No. 19. 
</P>
<P>
 Newcomers near the bottom of the chart included ABC's "McKenna," "On Our Own," 
"Blue Skies" (in its regular time slot) and "My So-Called Life"; NBC's 
"Something Wilder" and Fox's "New York Undercover," "Fortune Hunter," 
"M.A.N.T.I.S." and "Party of Five." Southland Ratings 
</P>
